What I say to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I travel often abroad and my foreign friends ask me each time, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is going on in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
First, make sure you do not create any misunderstandings about the 2016 elections.
Contrary to some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet, Trump fell short of winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
Nevertheless, Trump's victory highlights the real issue of rising social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly highlights the big difference between California and the Appalachian region.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income white Americans without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically have been at the bottom of inequality.
In 1999, the mortality rates among non-college-educated white Americans were about 30% lower than those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Furthermore, employment in industry, which had once been one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class individuals, has significantly declined over the last generation, accounting for only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to make things happen and bring jobs back to industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation are likely to make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you must not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his tantrums on Twitter and his scandalous contempt for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the audience's attention, and that the best way to do this is to make extreme statements without caring about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set the agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his constant self-centered campaign to actual governing attempts, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who loses the popular vote tends to move toward the political center to attract more support.
That is what George W. Bush succeeded in doing in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, proclaims that he won the popular vote and acts as if it were truly the case, pleasing his base voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations to the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services place him at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps.
Fourth, we must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling and ask if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but so were the founders of America.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' objective was not to ensure government harmony, but to limit political power through a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of that power difficult.
A joke about this says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to reign over us - impossible for him or anyone else.
Inefficiency has been serving freedom.
The Trump presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain of what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
However, so far, the courts, Congress, and the States have overseen this system of checks and balances within the administration, as Madison wished.
And the permanent executive agency officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I am less concerned about China's rise than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under US leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can say with certainty that it will continue.
The United States will need to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his administration suggest that he risks persisting with this approach.
The power to coerce and to convince of the United States, after all, comes largely from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and our planet's commons, is more uncertain.
The Trump Budget director speaks of a budget for coercive power, with budget cuts made to the State Department and to the UN system.
Other members of the government argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them about these issues.
But I cannot.
